40|$|This paper {{investigates the}} effects of a public <b>intermediate</b> <b>good</b> on the {{determinant}} of the trade pattern and the welfare effect, or the gains-from-trade, in a two-country, three-sector overlapping generations model. The main results of this paper are as follows. Firstly, the country with more public <b>intermediate</b> <b>good</b> (produced labor-intensively) imports an investment good (produced capital-intensively), if the country saves less compared to the other country. Secondly, the country with lower savings does not necessarily gain from trade even in an overlapping generations framework. These results {{can be attributed to the}} fact that the welfare effects are not directly dependent of the levels of capital but rather of the externalities of the public <b>intermediate</b> <b>good.</b> Key words: Three-sector overlapping generations model, terms-of-trade effect, capital accumulation effect, gains-from-trad...|$|R
40|$|This paper utilises a {{model of}} a small open economy that {{produces}} two traded goods by means of primary factors and a large number of varieties of a non-traded <b>intermediate</b> <b>good.</b> Unlike the traded goods, the production of each variety of the non-traded good is subject to internal economies of scale and monopolistic competition prevails in the <b>intermediate</b> <b>good</b> sector. The presence of internal economies in the <b>intermediate</b> <b>good</b> sector gives rise to external economies in the production of the final good sector. Within the context of the present study, interindustry and intra-industry trade takes place side by side. The model is used to examine the impact of tariffs and changes in factor endowments on allocation of resources and welfare. ...|$|R
